# **PHP Code Injection**
# PHP Code Injection happens when a web application takes user input and executes it as PHP code without proper validation.
## Step 1
# Set the severity to low 
# in the URL add the parameter placeholders as ?message= 
# URL should be like http://9.0.0.5/bWAPP/phpi.php?message=
# now give and random data after the parameter placholders 
# example - http://9.0.0.5/bWAPP/phpi.php?message=test
# You should be able to see test reflected in the page
# Try using phpinfo() command 
# example - http://9.0.0.5/bWAPP/phpi.php?message=phpinfo()
# This provides the complete PHP version details 
# we can also use system('<shell_command>');
# example - http://9.0.0.5/bWAPP/phpi.php?message=system('whoami'); or http://9.0.0.5/bWAPP/phpi.php?message=system('ls');
# The system will execute the php code and provides the information 

##Step 2 
# Set the severity to Medium 
# Medium and High Security level are using the <?php echo htmlspecialchars($_REQUEST["message"], ENT_QUOTES, "UTF-8");;?> 
which sanatize the input and prevent the running of external code provided by replacing the restricted words and it is considering our input as a text.


## Remediations
htmlspecialchars()
The most important remediation is not executing user input as code.
Avoid PHP functions such as Dangerous PHP functions to avoid:eval()assert()system()exec()shell_exec()passthru()
Allow only expected inputs 
If user input is printed on the page, encode it by adding htmlspecialchars()



